SIMPLE: gird
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gird
<hw>Gird</hw> <pr>(g⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Yard</er> a measure.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A stroke with a rod or switch; a severe spasm; a
twinge; a pang.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Conscience . . . is freed from many fearful <qex>girds</qex> and
twinges which the atheist feels.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cut; a sarcastic remark; a gibe; a
sneer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I thank thee for that <qex>gird</qex>, good Tranio.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gird</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gird
<hw>Gird</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Gird</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
and cf. <er>Girde</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike; to smite.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To slay him and to <qex>girden</qex> off his head.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sneer at; to mock; to gibe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Being moved, he will not spare to <qex>gird</qex> the gods.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gird</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gird
<hw>Gird</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To gibe; to sneer; to break a
scornful jest; to utter severe sarcasms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men of all sorts take a pride to <qex>gird</qex> at me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gird</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Gird
<hw>Gird</hw> <pr>(g⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Girt</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Girded</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Girding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>girden</ets>, <ets>gurden</ets>, AS. <ets>gyrdan</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>gurdian</ets>, D. <ets>gorden</ets>, OHG. <ets>gurten</ets>, G.
<ets>g⟦uum⟧rten</ets>, Icel. <ets>gyr⟦edh⟧a</ets>, Sw.
<ets>gjorda</ets>, Dan. <ets>giorde</ets>, Goth.
<ets>biga⟦iacute⟧rdan</ets> to begird, and prob. to E. <ets>yard</ets>
an inclosure. Cf. <er>Girth</er>, <pos>n. & v.</pos>, <er>Girt</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To encircle or bind with any
flexible band.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make fast, as clothing, by binding with a cord,
girdle, bandage, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To surround; to encircle, or encompass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That Nyseian isle,⟦br⟧
<qex>Girt</qex> with the River Triton.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To clothe; to swathe; to invest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>girded</qex> thee about with fine linen.</q> <rj><qau>Ezek.
xvi. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Son . . . appeared⟦br⟧
<qex>Girt</qex> with omnipotence.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To prepare; to make ready; to equip; <as>as, to
<ex>gird</ex> one's self for a contest</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast <qex>girded</qex> me with strength.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xviii. 39.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To gird on</b></col>, <cd>to put on; to fasten around or
to one securely, like a girdle; as, <xex>to gird on</xex> armor or a
sword.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not him that <qex>girdeth on</qex> his harness boast himself
as he that putteth it off.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings xx. 11.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To gird up</b></col>, <cd>to bind tightly with a girdle;
to support and strengthen, as with a girdle.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>girded up</qex> his loins, and ran before Ahab.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Kings xviii. 46.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Gird up</qex> the loins of your mind.</q> <rj><qau>1 Pet. i.
13.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>Girt up</b></col>; prepared or equipped, as for a journey
or for work, in allusion to the ancient custom of gathering the long
flowing garments into the girdle and tightening it before any exertion;
hence, adjectively, eagerly or constantly active; strenuous; striving.
⟦ldquo⟧A severer, more <xex>girt-up</xex> way of living.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>J.
C. Shairp.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Girder</ent>⟦br⟧
